# From notebook to production: Fine-tuning MedGemma with Cloud Run jobs

*Disclaimer: This guide is for informational and educational purposes only and is not a substitute for professional medical advice, diagnosis, or treatment. MedGemma is not intended to be used without appropriate validation, adaptation and/or making meaningful modification by developers for their specific use case. The outputs generated by MedGemma do not represent a finished or approved product and are not intended to directly inform clinical diagnosis, patient management decisions, treatment recommendations, or any other direct clinical practice applications. Performance benchmarks highlight baseline capabilities on relevant benchmarks, but even for image and text domains that constitute a substantial portion of training data, inaccurate model output is possible. It is not representative of compliance to any regulations or standard for quality, safety, or efficacy.  All outputs from MedGemma should be considered preliminary and require independent verification, clinical correlation, and further investigation through established research and development methodologies.*

In our previous post, [A step-by-step guide to fine-tuning MedGemma for breast tumor classification](https://cloud.google.com/blog/topics/developers-practitioners/a-step-by-step-guide-to-fine-tuning-medgemma-for-breast-tumor-classification?e=48754805&utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog), we walked through the process of fine-tuning the MedGemma model to teach it a specialized skillset withclassify breast cancer histopathology images, achieving a significant improvement in accuracy. Now, it's time to take that process from a research notebook to a repeatable, production workflow that uses Cloud Run jobs.

[Cloud Run jobs](https://cloud.google.com/run/docs/create-jobs?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog) is a fully managed service that lets you run containerized batch jobs that execute a script to completion. This function is perfect for our [fine-tuning](https://docs.cloud.google.com/run/docs/tutorials/gpu-finetune-with-jobs?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog) task, because we can package our Python script, its dependencies, and the environment into a container, and then run it on demand with a powerful GPU, without having to manage any infrastructure.

### Step 1.2 \- Get the code

Whether you're running locally or on the cloud, you'll need **the [code](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/devrel-demos/tree/finetune_medgemma/ai-ml/finetune_medgemma)**. After you open [**Cloud Shell**](http://shell.cloud.google.com.) or install your local [Google Cloud CLI](https://cloud.google.com/sdk/docs/install?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog), you need to clone the repository. The  finetune\_medgemma repository contains the finetune\_and\_evaluate.py script, a Dockerfile, and the requirements.txt file to your machine.

```shell

git clone https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/devrel-demos
cd devrel-demos/ai-ml/finetune_medgemma/

```

Before you proceed, take a moment to review the `finetune_and_evaluate.py` script.

You'll notice that the `load_data` function handles the entire data pipeline automatically. For this example, iIt starts by downloading the [**BreaKHis dataset**](https://web.inf.ufpr.br/vri/databases/breast-cancer-histopathological-database-breakhis/) directly using `kagglehub`, filtereds specifically for 100x magnification images, and—crucially—**balances the dataset** to ensure equal representation of benign and malignant samples.

To ensure that the fine-tuning process is quick and cost-effective for this tutorial, the finetune\_and\_evaluate.py script is set to use a subset of the available data. You can control the size of this subset by using the \--train-size and \--eval-size arguments.

**Note**: Cloud Run jobs have a maximum execution time of 60 minutes with **GPU** instances. To stay within this limit, we've set the training \--num\_epochs to 3 and limited the \--train-size to 200 samples.

In order to scaleFor a production-ready model, you would typically increase the training size and the number of epochs, but it's important to understand the trade-offs. While more data can improve a model's robustness, there's often a "sweet spot." The goal is to provide enough high-quality, diverse data for the model to learn general patterns without overfitting or incurring unnecessary training costs.

### 

Research has shown that for fine-tuning tasks, there can be diminishing returns after a certain data threshold, where adding more data yields little to no improvement. Finding this optimal dataset size is a key part of the machine learning lifecycle. For a deeper dive into this topic, I recommend exploring resources like [Sample Size Considerations for Fine-Tuning Large Language Models](https://ai.jmir.org/2024/1/e52095).

If you want to experiment with modifying the training size, see the Appendix for instructions.

Now, let's implement the proper solution using [Google Cloud Secret Manager](https://docs.cloud.google.com/secret-manager/docs/creating-and-accessing-secrets?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog). Storing secrets like our `HF_TOKEN` directly in code is a security risk. Secret Manager lets you store, manage, and access secrets as binary blobs or text strings. It provides a centralized and secured way to manage sensitive data. So we'll create a secret and grant our service account access to it.

   Use Secret Manager to store Hugging Face access token:

```

printf $HF_TOKEN | gcloud secrets versions add $SECRET_ID --data-file=-
```

```
gcloud secrets add-iam-policy-binding $SECRET_ID \
  --member serviceAccount:$SERVICE_ACCOUNT@$PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com \
  --role='roles/secretmanager.secretAccessor'
```

Later, when we create the Cloud Run Job, we use the `--set-secrets` flag to securely mount this secret as an environment variable within our container. One option for this is our Python script `finetune_and_evaluate.py` which is already written to automatically look for theis `HF_TOKEN` environment variable, so no code changes are needed.

## Step 2 \- Upload base model to cloud storage

**Pro tip: Staging the model in Cloud Storage** 

We recommend that you either store  ML models inside container images or optimize loading them from Cloud Storage. In this example, we're going to load the model from Cloud Storage. You can learn more about the trade-offs in [Best practices: Cloud Run jobs with GPUs](https://docs.cloud.google.com/run/docs/configuring/jobs/gpu-best-practices#model-loading-recommendations?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog). 

**Note:** Large models like MedGemma often exceed the disk space that's available in a standard Cloud Shell session. To get around this, we'll use a Python script to stream the model files directly from Hugging Face to Cloud Storage, without ever saving them to your local disk.

1. **Accept model license conditions.**   
   **Important:** The MedGemma model is publicly accessible, but you have to accept the conditions to access its files and content. Before running the transfer script, you must:  
1. Go to the [google/medgemma-4b-it model page](https://huggingface.co/google/medgemma-4b-it) on Hugging Face.  
2. Log in, review and decide tothen accept the license terms by clicking **Agree and Access Repository**.  
   Because we set the HF\_TOKEN environment variable earlier, your environment should already be authenticated with a [Hugging Face token](https://huggingface.co/settings/tokens) that has read access.  
1. **Create the transfer script**: Copy and paste the following Python script into your Cloud Shell. It uses the `HfFileSystem` to pipe the data directly to your bucket.

````
cat << 'EOF' > transfer_to_gcs.py
import os
from huggingface_hub import HfFileSystem
from google.cloud import storage
# Configuration
REPO_ID = "google/medgemma-4b-it"
BUCKET_NAME = os.environ.get("BUCKET_NAME")
if not BUCKET_NAME:
    print("Error: BUCKET_NAME environment variable is not set.")
    exit(1)
print(f"Starting disk-free transfer from {REPO_ID} to gs://{BUCKET_NAME}/base_model/...")
# Connect to HF and GCS
fs = HfFileSystem()
storage_client = storage.Client()
bucket = storage_client.bucket(BUCKET_NAME)
# List and transfer files
for hf_path in fs.glob(f"{REPO_ID}/**"):
    if fs.isdir(hf_path): continue
    
    # Define destination path
    rel_path = hf_path.replace(REPO_ID + "/", "")
    blob_name = f"base_model/{rel_path}"
    print(f"Streaming: {rel_path} -> gs://{BUCKET_NAME}/{blob_name}")
    # Pipe directly from source to destination
    with fs.open(hf_path, "rb") as source, bucket.blob(blob_name).open("wb") as dest:
        dest.write(source.read())
print("\n✅ Transfer complete!")
EOF
```
````

1. **Run the transfer script (should take 5-10 minutes)**:

```
uv run --with huggingface_hub --with google-cloud-storage transfer_to_gcs.py
```

To execute the script in a temporary, isolated environment, we use uv run. The \--with flag automatically installs the necessary huggingface-hub and google-cloud-storage libraries for this task without affecting your global Python installation. Note that uv is installed on the Google cloud shell by default, if you are running on a cloud workstation you would need to [create a virtual environment](https://docs.python.org/3/library/venv.html) and [install uv](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/getting-started/installation/#standalone-installer) to run this.

## Step 3 \- Build and push the container image 

Next, we need to package our fine-tuning script into a Docker container. This ensures that our code runs in a consistent and predictable environment.

### The requirements.txt file

This file lists all of the Python libraries that our script needs to run. It's crucial to pin the versions to help ensure reproducibility. Our requirements.txt file includes libraries like torch, transformers, datasets, peft, and trl. 

### The Dockerfile

The Dockerfile is a blueprint for building our container image. Here's a breakdown of what it does:

* FROM nvidia/cuda:12.1.1-runtime-ubuntu22.04: We start with a base image that includes the necessary NVIDIA CUDA drivers for the GPU.  
* RUN apt-get update && ...: We install Python and other system dependencies.  
* COPY requirements.txt .: We copy the requirements.txt file into the container.  
* RUN pip3 install \-r requirements.txt ...: We install the Python libraries.  
* COPY finetune\_and\_evaluate.py : We copy our fine-tuning script into the container.  
* CMD \["python3", "/app/inetune\_and\_evaluate.py", "\--device", "cuda"\]: This is the command that will be executed when the container starts, which runs our Python script.

The requirements.txt file and the Dockerfile are packaged into the container image and then pushed to the Artifact Registry repository that we created earlier. We're using DOCKER\_BUILDKIT=1 to enable Docker's modern and more efficient build engine, [BuildKit](https://docs.docker.com/build/buildkit/). The main advantage of using BuildKit here is its advanced caching capabilities, which we leverage with \--mount=type=cache in our Dockerfile when we install Python packages. This capability creates a persistent cache for our pip dependencies. Instead of re-downloading all the libraries on every build, BuildKit reuses them from the cache, which provides a huge speed boost on rebuilds and makes the development workflow much more efficient.

1. At the command line, go to the directory that contains the Dockerfile.  
2. **Build the image** by using the `DOCKER_BUILDKIT=1` environment variable that enables modern build features, specifically for this build command:

```
DOCKER_BUILDKIT=1 docker build -t $JOB_NAME .
```

3. Apply the registry format that's required by Artifact Registry by **tagging the image** that you just built:

```
docker tag $JOB_NAME $REGION-docker.pkg.dev/$PROJECT_ID/$AR_REPO/$IMAGE_NAME
```

4. Upload the tagged image to the remote repository by **pushing the image**:

```
docker push $REGION-docker.pkg.dev/$PROJECT_ID/$AR_REPO/$IMAGE_NAME
```

   If you get an authentication error when you try to push the image to the artifact registry, that's because your local Docker client hasn't been authorized to push images to the Google Artifact Registry in your region yet. To fix it, authorize the Docker client:

```
gcloud auth configure-docker $REGION-docker.pkg.dev
```

   When you're prompted to continue, type Y and then press **Enter**.

## Step 4 \- Create and execute the Cloud Run job

With our container image ready, we can now create and run the Cloud Run job.

1. **Create the job**: define job and specify the container image, environment variables (like the bucket name), and the necessary resources (like CPU, memory, and a GPU):

```shell

gcloud beta run jobs create $JOB_NAME \
  --region $REGION \
  --image $REGION-docker.pkg.dev/$PROJECT_ID/$AR_REPO/$IMAGE_NAME:latest \
  --set-env-vars BUCKET_NAME=$BUCKET_NAME \
  --set-secrets HF_TOKEN=$SECRET_ID:latest \
  --no-gpu-zonal-redundancy \
  --cpu 8.0 \
  --memory 32Gi \
  --labels dev-tutorial=blog-finetune-medgemma \
  --task-timeout 60m \
  --gpu 1 \
  --service-account $SERVICE_ACCOUNT@$PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com \
  --add-volume name=model-volume,type=cloud-storage,bucket=$BUCKET_NAME \
  --add-volume-mount volume=model-volume,mount-path=/mnt/gcs \  --args="--model-id,/mnt/gcs/base_model,--output-dir,/mnt/gcs/medgemma-finetuned,--gcs-output-path,gs://$PROJECT_ID-medgemma-finetuning/medgemma-finetuned,--num-epochs,3"
gcloud run jobs create $JOB_NAME \
  --region $REGION \
  --image $REGION-docker.pkg.dev/$PROJECT_ID/$AR_REPO/$IMAGE_NAME:latest \
  --set-env-vars BUCKET_NAME=$BUCKET_NAME \
  --set-secrets HF_TOKEN=$SECRET_ID:latest \
  --no-gpu-zonal-redundancy \
  --cpu 8.0 \
  --memory 32Gi \
  --labels dev-tutorial=blog-finetune-medgemma \
  --task-timeout 60m \
  --gpu 1 \
  --service-account $SERVICE_ACCOUNT@$PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com \
  --add-volume name=model-volume,type=cloud-storage,bucket=$BUCKET_NAME \
  --add-volume-mount volume=model-volume,mount-path=/mnt/gcs \
  --args="python3","/app/finetune_and_evaluate.py","--model-id","/mnt/gcs/base_model","--output-dir","/mnt/gcs/medgemma-finetuned","--gcs-output-path","gs://$BUCKET_NAME/medgemma-finetuned","--num-epochs","2"
 
```

2. **Execute the job**: The following command starts the job. The \--async flag returns control to your terminal immediately, while the job runs in the background.

```shell
gcloud beta run jobs execute $JOB_NAME --region $REGION --async 
```

The job will take some time to complete. You can monitor its progress in the Google Cloud console. When it's finished, your fine-tuned model will be saved in the Cloud Storage bucket that you created.

### Cloud Storage bucket (for the final model)

The primary artifact of the job is the fine-tuned model itself. The script saves the final, merged model files to the Cloud Storage bucket that you created.

* **Bucket name**: The bucket is named `$PROJECT_ID-medgemma-finetuning` based on the environment variables that you set up.  
* **Model path**: The script saves the model to a directory that's inside the job's container, which is mounted to your Cloud Storage bucket. Therefore, the model files will be at the root of your bucket. The script confirms that the files are saved with the final log message: "✓ Final model saved successfully."

By using [Cloud Run jobs](https://cloud.google.com/run/docs/create-jobs?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog), we've transformed our fine-tuning process from a one-off notebook experiment into a scalable and repeatable workflow. This is a crucial  step  in moving from research to production, because it lets you retrain and update your models with ease and consistency. Although the model that we created in this guide used a small dataset for demonstration purposes only, you now have a the process knowledge to achieve your own projectproduction-ready process. By simply increasing the dataset size in your Dockerfile as described earlier, you can use this exact workflow to build a more robust, production-grade model.

This powerful combination of fine-tuning open models like MedGemma and leveraging serverless tools like Cloud Run opens up a world of possibilities for building specialized AI solutions.

Now that you have a repeatable process for building robust fine-tunedcreating production-ready models, the journey doesn't end. Continue your learning by exploring how to [host your fine-tuned model on Cloud Run](https://cloud.google.com/run/docs/tutorials/gpu-finetune-with-jobs?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog) for real time inferencelive predictions or how to [run batch inference using GPUs](https://cloud.google.com/run/docs/tutorials/jobs-gpu-batch-inference?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog) for large-scale offline tasks. For a different perspective, see the recent post on [building a production multimodal fine-tuning pipeline](https://cloud.google.com/blog/topics/developers-practitioners/building-a-production-multimodal-fine-tuning-pipeline?utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog), which explores using other powerful runtimes like [Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE)](https://cloud.google.com/kubernetes-engine?hl=en&utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog) and [Google Cloud Batch](https://cloud.google.com/batch?hl=en&utm_campaign=CDR_0x91b1edb5_default_b451009169&utm_medium=external&utm_source=blog).

## Appendix

You can adjust the training size parameters by modifying the arguments that are passed in the CMD instruction of the Dockerfile.

Modified Dockerfile CMD:

```
# Runs the script with updated training and evaluation sizes
CMD ["python3", "/app/finetune_and_evaluate.py", "--device", "cuda", "--train-size", "1000", "--eval-size", "500"]
```

After you make this change to the Dockerfile, you need to rebuild your container image. The Cloud Run job will then execute the script with these new, larger dataset sizes to produce a more robustly trained model. You can also pass command arguments into Cloud Run in your job creation command, in which case you don't have to rebuild the container.
